# Equipment

## Portals

If you're just testing the waters, then it's probably easiest to use your preferred web browser, together with a web portal that can translate between the Web and the SmolNet protocols (Gopher, Gemini, etc).

=> http://portal.mozz.us/ (Gemini, Spartan, Gopher...)
=> https://gopherproxy.meulie.net/ (Gopher only)
!- TODO: more portal links. Does geminiprotocol.net have some?

## Clients (Browsers... but not of the Web)

If you're done just kicking the tires of SmolNet, and want to explore it in greater depth, then you want a client (like a browser) for that. Most gemcaps that support logins, use client TLS certificates as both identification and authentication, rather than username-and-password, so a client that can generate and manage different client certificates is particularly helpful for taking a more active and participatory role in the community (as opposed to just observing).

I recommend Lagrange, which currently appears to be the most full-featured and comfortable-to-use client, is available on multiple platforms, and has support for a number of SmollNet protocols, and convenience features.

=> ../why-client/ Why would you use a client?

